# Circuit Breaker Sizing

Objective

To understand how to properly select circuit breakers based on load current and fault current.


## System Data

Case 1:
- Transformer = 1 MVA
- Voltage = 415 V
- Fault Current ≈ 28 kA

Case 2:
- Transformer = 2 MVA
- Voltage = 415 V
- Fault Current ≈ 50 kA


## Key Calculations

### Full Load Current (FLC)

Formula:

I = S / (√3 × V)

Case 1:
I ≈ 1391 A

Case 2:
I ≈ 2783 A


## Breaker Current Rating

Rule:

Breaker rating ≥ 125% of FLC

Case 1:
≈ 1800 A

Case 2:
≈ 3500 – 3600 A

---

## Breaking Capacity

Rule:

Breaking capacity ≥ Fault current × safety margin

Case 1:
≈ 36 kA

Case 2:
≈ 63 kA


## Key Concepts Learned

- Breaker sizing is based on both load and fault conditions
- Current rating and breaking capacity serve different purposes
- Safety margins are necessary for reliable system design
- Standard breaker sizes must be used in real applications


##  Engineering Insight

Increasing transformer size increases fault current, requiring higher breaker capacity. Proper sizing ensures both operational reliability and system protection.


## Conclusion

Breaker selection is a critical part of power system design and must be based on accurate calculations and engineering judgment rather than assumptions.
